VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and sterile, which is why I picked out an art navo aesthetic for this. With energy costs at a low, I like to imagine people being more inclined to focus on their expendable income on the arts. Aesthetically, my vision of solar punk'

[05:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is very similar to steampunk, but with electronic technology in an art navo veneer. So, it\'s not just the projected hope of the more left-leaning individuals of a future run on clean energy, but a return to artisanship'

[05:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that\'s been long forgotten. In this world, one would have to wonder if the division of labor still exists. Prior to the industrial era, or more particularly during the Renaissance, it was actually'

[06:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'considered an ideal to be a jack of all trades. The guild system, for example, didn\'t just teach people one skill. It was encouraged to have multiple skills. Craftsmen would be trained in multiple trades, like goldsmiths turned'

[06:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'architects, for example. But when the division of labor came onto the scene, we started hyper specializing. And with that became a loss of much of that creative spark. So much effort and training goes into nurturing one\'s skill that not much energy is left over which'

[06:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'leads many to binging TV or Tik Tok at the end of the day not indulging in their creative pursuits. So it seems that in this world artistic embellishment is much more celebrated. Buildings can be adorned not because'

[06:50] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it\'s profitable to do so but because it actually brings people joy to not only create beautiful things but also to look at beautiful things. Wow. Who would have thought? But if we prioritize beautiful'

