[08:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'But what\'s solar punk like in regards to money? In solar punk, there\'s not one singular'

[08:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'agreed upon economic system, but there\'s a theme that comes up pretty often on how a solar punk world would most likely work. First, this is a postcist society. Rather than focusing on endless economic'

[08:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'growth, it shifts to regeneration. Instead of garbage being thrown to the oceans and beaches, things are reused. Instead of products being made with as lowquality materials as possible'

[08:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'so that people keep having to buy new stuff, quality is given utmost importance. Instead of replacing, there\'s repairing. Second, resources like water, energy, and knowledge are shared rather'

[09:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'than privatized. As we know in capitalism, these are not seen as basic needs that should be available to everyone regardless of income. But in solar punk, they are. Third, instead of corporate or state'

[09:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'monopolies, community ownership takes hold. So things like community solar grids and farms that are cooperatively owned would be more of a thing rather than pure privatization. But there\'s still, of course, privatization in the'

[09:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'way of homes and land. Privacy is important, but the distinction would be private in the form of retreat rather than capital to be leveraged. There is a balance between cooperative ownership and private ownership. And no, landlords'

[09:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'wouldn\'t exist in this hypothetical world. And fourth, decentralization. If a solar punk society were to work, most things would have to be decentralized. So banks that squeeze money out of'

[10:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'people through interest rates and silly fees would have to go. Instead of having intermediaries at every turn, there would have to be much more emphasis on peer-to-peer networks. And as far as currency, there is a lot of flexibility.'

[10:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'There have been a few different proposed ideas in the solar punk community, but the most common one seems to be a shift from our current fiat currency. In our current system, as most know, there\'s a lot of greed. Our fiat currency isn\'t'

[10:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'backed by anything, and a lot of our current problems can be traced back to that. It makes it a lot easier for the gap to keep getting wider and wider between the upper classes and the lower classes. Since our currency isn\'t backed'

[10:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'by anything, money is just printed to meet the demands of an abstract economy. When money is printed, often that comes with inflation. For the wealthy, inflation pushes up the value of the assets they already own, like stocks and'

[10:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'real estate. So inflation actually appreciates their assets. And on top of that, they have easy access to credit since they\'re low-risk borrowers. So they can keep investing in building wealth. For them, it\'s a win-win. But'

[11:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'for the lower classes, it\'s a different story. As inflation kicks in, the value of their money drops and everything gets more expensive. Wages rarely keep up with inflation, so they end up being'

[11:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'able to buy less with the same paycheck. They also don\'t have a bunch of assets to fall back on, so rising prices hit them harder. It makes it really tough to break out of that cycle of poverty. At the end of the day, printing more money'

[11:31] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'is just another way the system favors the rich. So, how do we battle this? We know now the limits of our current system, but to return back to trade and barter seems primitive. The reason money came into existence was because of the'

[11:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'limits of that system. There\'s no standardized value in a trade and barter system. And both parties need to want what the other has to offer. If one person wants shoes and the other wants food, there\'s no easy way to trade'

[11:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'unless the exchange aligns at that moment. So, what\'s a better solution? For a lot of proponents of solar punk, the answer would be an emphasis on local decentralized currencies. And this is'

[12:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'the point where most people start to scratch their heads because an economy like this would simply not work in our current system. We are far too globalized and dependent on products overseas. To even entertain the idea of'

[12:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'a system like this seems silly. And some of the proponents of the solar punk vision admit this. So for those who favor global trade, a more global digital currency is not out of the realm of possibility. But it also should be'

[12:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'noted that in a solar punk world, globalization and mass production simply do not exist at the scale it does now. I do believe we have a unique opportunity to be one of the drivers and large'

