AUDIO: 'investors for the global capital market. So it\'s imperative for us at BlackRock to to continue to build out our platforms worldwide in South America and in Asia and continue to build out in the'

[12:59] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'US and and Europe. It is it means we have to have a much greater global mindset. Taking advantage of people overseas by the use of cheap labor and sweat shops in order to extract as much'

[13:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'profit as possible is really the antithesis of a solar punk vision. They wake up, they have breakfast, they go to work, they work a solid shift, they come back to their dormatory, they sleep.'

[13:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'It\'s a very dehumanizing place and that the workers are little more than the machines there. Employees live in dormitories 8 to a room common for factories in China. Often roommates though will not know each other\'s names.'

[13:36] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Do you know these guys? Do you know their names? Do you know where they\'re from and and all that kind of stuff? She arrived 3 days ago. I don\'t know her name, she says. there\'s no real sense of community there and I think that is one'

[13:48] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of the the significant factors behind this um alarming number of suicides. No, instead of globalization, the focus is on localization. So perhaps an economy like this would work in this type of'

[14:01] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'local community. It\'s much easier to keep track of reciprocal actions if you\'re interacting with people in close proximity to you compared to buying from a manufacturer 4,000 m away. Instead of what we have now, a funnel economy where'

[14:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'all the wealth gets funneled to the top, there would likely be a circular economy where everything is in fluid motion, drastically lowering the odds of wealth hoarding. But what would a local economy like this look like? And is there a name'

[14:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'for this? This would be called a gift economy. If we look at tribes as an example, where this type of economy likely still exists in its purest form, the act of giving is often not about'

[14:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'expecting a direct return, but ensuring that the community continues to function in a state of mutual support. These practices are based on the understanding that well-being is a communal responsibility, not a purely every man'

[14:52] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'for himself mindset. So, let\'s use an example. Sarah needs a new table for her home. So, she approaches Tom, who is a skilled carpenter in the community. Instead of'

[15:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'offering money or barter, Sarah asks Tom if he can help her build the table. Tom agrees to help Sarah with a table, but doesn\'t expect money. The gift economy is based on community reciprocity. So, Tom and Sarah have an understanding that'

[15:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'helping each other is the true exchange, not money. Tom works with the community sustainably sourced wood, which is shared among others for projects like this. The wood may have been harvested from fallen trees or from a'

[15:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'community-managed forest. Whatever it is, it\'s ethically sourced. Pure solid wood. Sarah, in turn, feels relief knowing that the table she needed but didn\'t know how to build is getting built. After the table is built, Sarah'

[15:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'has her new piece of furniture. And in gratitude, Sarah offers to help sew him some new clothes. There\'s reciprocity, mutual agreement. I know this seems foreign in a world where we can\'t really'

[15:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'wrap our heads around things not being commodified. But if we were to put on our nostalgia goggles, this was the essence of a perfect America not too long ago. So many people look back with rosecolored glasses on how people used'

[16:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to talk to their neighbors and be more involved in their local communities. The proverbial phrase, "People used to knock on the neighbors door for a cup of sugar," is often uttered by those who yearn for a bygone era. But that time is'

[16:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'long gone and the good parts of it can only be returned really if we learn to stop commodifying everything and put more emphasis on community instead of every man for himself. It\'s I appreciate'

[16:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'that so much that I\'ll use my skills and talents in the best way I can and I\'ll get the next one. But what does the research say about this type of economy? Does it'

[16:44] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'work? In the study gift exchange and reciprocity in competitive experimental markets, researchers explored this very topic. The goal of this study was to see how gift exchange and reciprocity influence behavior in competitive'

[16:58] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'markets. In the first sentence of the introduction of the paper, it\'s interesting to see them make this statement. Most economic models are based on the assumption of rational and selfish agents. And yeah, that kind of tracks. Our current system is pretty'

[17:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'much running on the fumes of this premise. But here\'s where it gets interesting. The study actually found some pretty good evidence for the contrary. The setup was this. There were two groups of participants, buyers and'

[17:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'sellers. Sellers had to decide how much quality to offer based on the price the buyers chose to offer. And there were two different markets. There was the competitive market where buyers and sellers were acting like regular'

[17:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'competitors trying to get the best deal for themselves. And then there was the reciprocity market where the idea of gift exchange was introduced. Sellers in this market were encouraged to respond to how fairly they were treated by'

[17:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'buyers in the past. Meaning, if sellers got a higher price, they\'d give better quality. What they found from this study was a few different things. First, reciprocity matters. The study showed that reciprocity, the idea of I\'ll help'

[18:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you if you help me, actually influences economic decisions more than you would think. When one person gives something first, like a gift, the receiver tends to reciprocate with something in return.'

[18:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Surprisingly, even in competitive markets where there isn\'t an immediate expectation of a return. Second, they discovered that giftgiving made people more cooperative in a way that regular money exchanges didn\'t. Since people'

[18:25] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'expected future reciprocity, they were more likely to be fair and work together. Third, there was a preference for social cohesion over rational self-interest. The study found that people often make decisions based on'

[18:38] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'social preferences like wanting to maintain good relationships rather than maximizing their own personal gain. Basically, people aren\'t purely selfish robots. We care about fairness, reputation, and not being that guy who'

[18:51] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'takes without giving back. And finally, the one that surprised me the most, cooperation actually makes markets work better. When people engage in reciprocal giftlike exchanges, markets actually become more efficient, not less. On the'

[19:05] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'other hand, when the competition is cutthroat, things tend to get more chaotic and inefficient. So, ironically, the whole I\'ll take mine mindset might not be as effective as capitalism likes'

[19:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to pretend. So an economy like this might work but of course it would have to be on a small scale yet still tapped into the larger population in ways of information sharing and skill'

[19:29] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'development. And again even if a gift economy wouldn\'t work smallcale local digital currencies could work in place of fiat currency. Next we should also mention some downsides of a solar punk'

[19:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'vision. Some critics view solar punk as anarcho primitivism or eco-fascism, while others view it as naive optimism. And for more radical or unrealistic approaches that some solar punk'

[19:55] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'enthusiasts might have, I can see where they\'re coming from. Everyone has a different flavor of how they view their own solar punk. It\'s not like a one-sizefits-all sort of thing. And I think that\'s the beauty of it. Instead'

[20:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of capitalism where the proponents relish in the idea that anyone can build their own empire of wealth or the communist who believes everything should be shared, I think solar punk is a decent middle ground. Its focus is on envisioning and keeping things open in a'

[20:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'more democratic way rather than saying this is how it has to be. You know, I\'ve ragged on capitalism a lot on this channel. But if we\'re being totally honest, communism hasn\'t really nailed'

[20:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'it either. And the core issue, it\'s the same for both. Power doesn\'t just go away. Most attempts at a communist society have required a strong central authority in order to enforce the system. Research has shown we\'re only'

[20:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'able to support about 150 relationships. We don\'t care about the millions of people in our country who will never speak to or see. Why should you work hard to support someone else? It doesn\'t sound fair and it doesn\'t make sense.'

[20:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Likewise, in the government, you have access to all this money and you\'re supposed to dole it out evenly. But most of the people you aren\'t ever going to meet or see. But your family, your friends, they could benefit if they get just a little bit more. We won\'t ever'

[21:10] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'see communism succeed. Because in my opinion, you can\'t have a political ideology that goes against human nature. Those who take a liking to the solar punk vision are usually not described as communist, but perhaps anti-'

[21:22] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'athoritarian and collectivist. There\'s excitement for local governments and trading skills and knowledge between these local governments, not so much for the red tape of large institutions. So, I\'ve spoken a lot about the economy of a'

[21:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'system like this, but I want to bring it back to the vision from the beginning of this video. We\'ve forgotten how to work together. Not because we don\'t want to, but because everything has turned into'

[21:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'something that has to be bought, sold, or monetized. But just imagine for a second a world where we had access to things like renewable energy, giving us so much more free time. That would leave us more time to actually do the things'

[22:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'we love to innovate more. How much happier could we be as a society? And if resources were in the hands of everyone instead of hoarded by the wealthiest few, how much faster would we advance? I think about this a lot, especially when'

[22:15] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'I see some really bright kids being denied a higher education just because they can\'t afford it. Or when someone has a dream, an amazing idea for a business, but they\'ll never get the chance to make it real because they'

[22:27] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'don\'t have the money, the connections, or even the time to pursue it. It makes me wonder, how much human potential are we wasting simply because we\'ve built a system that locks people out instead of lifting them up?'

[22:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'It feels bizarre still in a way to see people out. The way you grew up, most were holed up in their homes, sifting and consuming silently on their phones. Neighbors rarely spoke to each other.'

[22:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'You only ever saw them in passing, stepping out of their cars, only to quickly disappear behind the closed doors of the zone of isolation. The suburbs were not a place for you, where perfection was expected and loneliness'

[23:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'thrived. But this time, things were different. In this life, you no longer sit at a desk crunching numbers into a data set as you had done before. Now you gift your skills to those who truly'

[23:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'appreciate it personally. You help. You don\'t sell. Before us humans viewed ourselves as outside of nature, contributing waste on scales never seen before. Every man for himself. Now we'

[23:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'are a part of it. An ecosystem in motion. Together yet separate. Whole yet independent. [Music]'

